sentences: Margaret Fingerhut (born 30 March 1955) is a British classical pianist.
Fingerhut's career was launched when she was selected as a Young Musician of the Year by the Greater London Arts Association in 1981.
Fingerhut's career was launched when she was selected as a Young Musician of the Year by the Greater London Arts Association in 1981.
She made her London debut at the Wigmore Hall in the same year, and first played in the Royal Festival Hall in 1983.
She made her London debut at the Wigmore Hall in the same year, and first played in the Royal Festival Hall in 1983.

Her discs on the Chandos label include works by Bainton, Bax, Berkeley, Bloch, Dukas, Falla, Grieg, Howells, Leighton, Moeran, Novák, Stanford, Suk and Tansman, as well as several pioneering collections of 19th century Russian and early 20th century French piano music.

Her discs on the Chandos label include works by Bainton, Bax, Berkeley, Bloch, Dukas, Falla, Grieg, Howells, Leighton, Moeran, Novák, Stanford, Suk and Tansman, as well as several pioneering collections of 19th century Russian and early 20th century French piano music.

Her discs on the Chandos label include works by Bainton, Bax, Berkeley, Bloch, Dukas, Falla, Grieg, Howells, Leighton, Moeran, Novák, Stanford, Suk and Tansman, as well as several pioneering collections of 19th century Russian and early 20th century French piano music.

Her CD of encores, "Endless Song", was Featured Album of the Week on Classic FM and was selected as "Editor's Choice" in Pianist as well as being awarded an "Outstanding" accolade in International Record Review.
Fingerhut is a Visiting Tutor at the Royal Birmingham Conservatoire where she was made an Honorary Fellow in 2015.
She is a regular guest at summer schools such as Dartington International Summer School, Chetham's International Summer School for Pianists and Jackdaws.

She is a regular guest at summer schools such as Dartington International Summer School, Chetham's International Summer School for Pianists and Jackdaws.
She has given masterclasses in the USA, Canada, Japan and China, and has been on the jury of competitions such as the BBC Young Musician of the Year.
In 2019 Fingerhut devised and performed a recital tour around the UK which raised £88,000 for refugees in the UK - this represents £1,000 for each of the keys of a grand piano.
Her achievement was recognised with a ‘Champion of Sanctuary’ award by the City of Sanctuary UK in 2019.
